or to manage agendas and follow-ups.	Do_1 \r\n\r\nFormally constitute the committee and circulate the approved charter.\r\n\r\nSchedule recurring meetings with published agendas and pre-meeting briefings.\r\n\r\nEstablish dashboards and KPIs to monitor security posture, risk ratings, and compliance progress.\r\n\r\nReview and approve security policies, standards, and risk treatment plans.\r\n\r\nTrack progress on major initiatives ∩┐╜ vulnerability management, compliance audits, training programs.\r\n\r\nMaintain detailed minutes of meetings with assigned action owners and due dates.\r\n\r\nProvide executive reporting to the Board or senior management on security posture.\r\n\r\nCoordinate with Legal, Risk, and Compliance teams for cross-functional security alignment.\r\n\r\nDo_2 \r\n\r\nConduct periodic meetings (at least twice a year) to review major security events.\r\n\r\nKeep informal notes or action items in shared documents.\r\n\r\nDiscuss only critical risks and incidents needing leadership input.\r\n\r\nCirculate summary updates via email to stakeholders.	Check_1 (High Priority ∩┐╜ Strong Review)\r\n\r\nConduct semi-annual reviews of the ISGC∩┐╜s effectiveness ∩┐╜ meeting frequency, attendance, and action closure.\r\n\r\nEvaluate alignment between committee outputs and organizational security goals.\r\n\r\nReview implementation progress of decisions taken during meetings.\r\n\r\nAudit the documentation ∩┐╜ agendas, minutes, action items, and status trackers.\r\n\r\nGather feedback from members and stakeholders to improve governance efficiency.\r\n\r\nEnsure compliance alignment with security governance and leadership responsibilities.\r\n\r\nCheck_2 \r\n\r\nReview committee minutes annually for decision tracking.\r\n\r\nVerify whether meetings occurred as scheduled.\r\n\r\nEnsure at least one review of major risks was conducted each year.\r\n\r\nCheck if open action items are followed up.	Act_1 \r\n\r\nUpdate the committee charter and membership annually based on organizational or regulatory changes.\r\n\r\nIntroduce subcommittees for areas like cloud security, privacy, or DevSecOps as the organization matures.\r\n\r\nImplement automated dashboards to visualize risk and compliance metrics in real time.\r\n\r\nProvide leadership training on emerging cybersecurity governance trends.\r\n\r\nEnhance integration with business continuity and strategic risk management processes.\r\n\r\nReview and improve communication mechanisms between ISGC and operational teams.\r\n\r\nAct_2 \r\n\r\nUpdate the meeting calendar and participant list annually.\r\n\r\nSimplify reporting templates for better participation.\r\n\r\nAdd new members or advisors when needed.\r\n\r\nDocument and share lessons learned from previous meetings.		\N	\N	[]	\N	00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001	5047203c-b001-411b-865e-1f1ca19b1d0a	\N	\N	CADP
65	TVM-002	To check with Security team	To check with Praveen	Cybersecurity	guru.g@cavininfotech.com	Third-Party & Vendor Management	Establish Vendor Security Requirements	Define security requirements and include appropriate security clauses in vendor contracts	A.5.20	ID.SC-2	CC9.2	Art 28	Sec 43A	Req 12.8	164.502(e)	High	Not Implemented	2025-11-06 00:00:00+05:30	Guru to check with Murali	[]	Plan 1 :\r\n1.Develop detailed supplier agreements with clauses on data protection, access control, incident reporting, and audit rights.\r\n2.Ensure all suppliers align with your organization∩┐╜s information classification and security requirements.\r\n3.Maintain a supplier risk register and review agreements periodically to verify compliance and control effectiveness.\r\nPlan 2 :\r\n1Add a basic information security clause in supplier contracts referencing confidentiality and data protection.\r\n2.Keep a simple list of active suppliers with agreement status tracked.	Do_1:\r\n1.Communicate your security requirements to suppliers clearly before onboarding.\r\n2.Ensure they acknowledge and accept these obligations in the contract.\r\n3.Verify that suppliers implement basic controls (e.g., secure access, encryption, backup).\r\nDo_2:\r\n1.Maintain a supplier register listing all contracts and their security terms.\r\n2.Ensure suppliers have trained staff, incident response plans, and sub-supplier controls if applicable.\r\n3.Share incident handling procedures and security contacts with them.	Check_1:\r\n1.Monitor supplier compliance ∩┐╜ review performance reports, audits, and certifications (like ISO 27001, SOC 2).\r\n2.Ask for evidence of controls or test results periodically.\r\n3.Track incidents or breaches related to supplier activities.\r\nCheck_2:\r\n1.Review supplier agreements annually or when business/risk changes.\r\n2.Evaluate whether controls are still effective and relevant.\r\n3.Record any gaps, expired clauses, or missing compliance evidence.	Act_1:\r\n1.Address any non-compliance or weaknesses with corrective actions or updated contracts.\r\n2.Communicate improvements to suppliers and set deadlines.\r\n3.Terminate or suspend risky suppliers if they fail to meet agreed requirements.\r\nAct_2:\r\n1.Improve the supplier management process ∩┐╜ update templates, checklists, and onboarding steps.\r\n2.Conduct refresher training for procurement and vendor management teams.\r\n3.Include supplier risk assessment results in your management review meetings.		\N	\N	[]	\N	00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001	25b3ac99-ad72-4d45-9948-6803101b597c	\N	\N	CADP
